287–Deceased","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","about 1272":"about 1272","about 1270":"about 1270","abt 1281":"about 1281","1230":"1230","1350":"1350","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","about 1245":"about 1245","Craignish, Argyllshire, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Campbell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camble","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Malcolm Campbell 5th of Craignish was born about 1250, in Craignish, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Dugald Campbell IV Laird of Craignish, was 27 and his mother, Jennet Lamont, was 22. He married Mrs Malcolm Campbell about 1270, in Argyll, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1290, in Scotland, at the age of 41."},"et":{"Abt 1250–1290":"umbes 1250–1290","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1250–1290":"1250–1290","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1272–1350":"1272–1350","1281–Female":"1281–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","about 1272":"umbes 1272","about 1270":"umbes 1270","abt 1281":"umbes 1281","1230":"1230","1350":"1350","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","about 1245":"umbes 1245","Craignish, Argyllshire, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1250–1290":"noin 1250–1290","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1250–1290":"1250–1290","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1272–1350":"1272–1350","1281–Female":"1281–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","about 1272":"noin 1272","about 1270":"noin 1270","abt 1281":"noin 1281","1230":"1230","1350":"1350","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","about 1245":"noin 1245","Craignish, Argyllshire, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland"},"fr":{"Abt 1250–1290":"environ 1250–1290","1245–Male":"1245–Déc